'''Buddhism in Nicaragua''' has existed since the late 19th century, after immigration from countries with [[Buddhist]] populations, mainly [[China]]. Although sources are not readily available, Buddhists are believed to constitute 0.1% of the total population in [[Nicaragua]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Religious freedom nation page |url=http://religiousfreedom.lib.virginia.edu/nationprofiles/Nicaragua/rbodies.html |accessdate=2007-04-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060829070157/http://religiousfreedom.lib.virginia.edu/nationprofiles/Nicaragua/rbodies.html |archivedate=2006-08-29 |df= }}</ref>

==History==
Buddhism was brought to Nicaragua in the late 19th century when the [[Overseas Chinese|Chinese]] started arriving, many of which came from [[Guangdong|Gu«éngd≈çng]] (Âπø‰∏ú) province.

